<p><a href="https://www.google.com/url?q=https%3A%2F%2Fredcap.med.usc.edu%2Fsurveys%2F%3Fs%3DJ7KEL4YTKT&amp;sa=D&amp;sntz=1&amp;usg=AFQjCNGgmJPVlIxKzdq9Pd16K5HC0kstRQ"><img src="https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/4PBkwa0Cmx6ps0-OLOvLUrDWPZhdMXfRzVAcAivhTmQmfBnj7B3sukS1JpSR3KkDfhvQAblIC0Pw6H4jLONp4eqKQnc5nZ7ZdZ76b44GLfxilk41ens=w1280" alt="" /></a></p>

<h3 id="hkgj4xyb10ri4-zfr3q-omqg5e-dirltr-tabindex-1">{#h.kgj4xyb10ri4 .zfr3Q .OmQG5e dir=”ltr” tabindex=”-1”}</h3>

<p><a href="#h.kgj4xyb10ri4"></a></p>

<p>John Fund has found another excellent case example–Hong Kong Flu of
1968, so far much worse than C19– where social isolation controls were
not even contemplated. A lot happened in 1968, I was there. Even 130,000
extra US flu deaths did not shut schools, businesses, or force people to
socially isolate. No one wore masks. It was not in the top news stories
of 1968 with the MLK and RFK assassinations, the riots, the Chicago
convention, presidential election, Vietnam, summer of love, etc.</p>

